    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1967-05-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1967-05-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="202"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d202">
                <head>202. Memorandum From the Presidentʼs Special Assistant (<persName
                        corresp="#p_RWW1" type="from">Rostow</persName>) to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_JLB1" type="to">Johnson</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d202fn1">Source: <persName>Johnson</persName>
                        Library, National Security File, Country File, Dominican Republic, Vol.
                        XVII. Secret. An “L” on the memorandum indicates that the President saw
                        it.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1967-05-19">May 19, 1967</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Dominican Situation</item>
                </list>
                <p>This is in response to your concern over how things are going in the Dominican
                    Republic.</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">The Background</hi>
                </p>
                <p>Up until March 21—when unknown assailants tried to kill <persName
                        corresp="#p_IA1">Imbert</persName>—<persName corresp="#p_BJ1"
                        >Balaguer</persName> was making slow but steady progress in consolidating
                    his political position. Months of relative stability had given the business
                    community a new confidence and the economy was starting to gather some
                    momentum.</p>
                <p>Since March, the political and economic climate has changed and <persName
                        corresp="#p_BJ1">Balaguer</persName>ʼs position weakened. Failure to solve
                    the <persName corresp="#p_IA1">Imbert</persName> case—followed by a series of
                    other murders and attempted murders—has made the public apprehensive. The
                    economic sector is uneasy and cautious. And anti-<persName corresp="#p_BJ1"
                        >Balaguer</persName> elements on the right and left have launched a campaign
                    to pin the “Trujillista” label on him. As might be expected the <gloss
                        target="#t_PRD1">PRD</gloss> is in the forefront of this effort.</p>
                <pb facs="0519" n="484" xml:id="pg_484"/>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <persName corresp="#p_BJ1">Balaguer</persName>ʼs Strength and Weaknesses</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_BJ1">Balaguer</persName>ʼs situation is not critical, but
                    his hold has been shaken. He still has going for him: <list>
                        <item>—the support of most Dominicans who long for tranquillity.</item>
                        <item>—basic military support.</item>
                        <item>—our strong backing.</item>
                        <item>—confidence in himself.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Working against him are: <list>
                        <item>—his vulnerability to the “Trujillista” charge because of certain
                            elements around him.</item>
                        <item>—his lack of political sophistication in dealing with the noncommunist
                            opposition.</item>
                        <item>—the violence which continues to plague the country.</item>
                        <item>—his inability to delegate authority and the poor management capacity
                            of his administration.</item>
                        <item>—a difficult balance of payments and fiscal situation.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">What we can do</hi>
                </p>
                <p>I met with the Dominican Review Group (<persName corresp="#p_CG1"
                        >Gordon</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_VCR1">Vance</persName>, <persName
                        corresp="#p_FD1">FitzGerald</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_KFD1"
                        >Kohler</persName> and Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_CJH1"
                        >Crimmins</persName>) two weeks ago to review the situation. We agreed on a
                    set of short-term courses of action (copy attached)<note n="2" xml:id="d202fn2"
                        >Entitled “Short Term Courses of Action in the Dominican Republic,” May 5,
                        it is a duplicate of the attachment to <ref target="#d200">Document
                            200</ref> minus the “Background” section.</note> which <persName
                        corresp="#p_CJH1">Crimmins</persName> is carrying out.</p>
                <p>The most important of these is to persuade <persName corresp="#p_BJ1"
                        >Balaguer</persName> to curb terrorism and restore public confidence. He has
                    taken two steps in this direction: <list>
                        <item>—a strong public statement that he will not tolerate terrorism and
                            will take energetic measures to stamp it out, and</item>
                        <item>—appointment of a high level committee to make a thorough
                            investigation of the National Police Force, which is suspected of being
                            involved in some of the terrorism. (Unfortunately, <persName
                                corresp="#p_BJ1">Balaguer</persName> did <hi rend="italic">not</hi>
                            include distinguished people from outside the government—another example
                            of his lack of political judgment.)</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_GGH1">Garcia Godoy</persName> called on Bill
                    Bowdler Wednesday<note n="3" xml:id="d202fn3">May 17; no record of this
                        conversation has been found.</note> evening prior to going to Santo Domingo.
                    He too was concerned about trends. He will talk to <persName corresp="#p_BJ1"
                        >Balaguer</persName> about political strategy in dealing with terrorism. He
                    will also try to persuade the <gloss target="#t_PRD1">PRD</gloss> to moderate
                    its opposition. Bill encouraged him to do this. <persName corresp="#p_GGH1"
                        >Garcia Godoy</persName> said he would give us his impressions as soon as he
                    got back. He expressed deep appreciation for your action on a special sugar
                    quota for the <gloss target="#t_DR1">DR</gloss>. He noted that this strong
                        <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> support for <persName corresp="#p_BJ1"
                        >Balaguer</persName> would be a stabilizing factor.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Walt</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
